column168: Driver was at a customer location and noticed product leaking out of box trailer.  Product was noted to be sodium hypochlorite (12.5% solution), due to the characteristic odor.  The rear of the trailer was opened and a drum of sodium hypochlorite was found to be leaking from a hole in the bottom near the edge caused by a nail protruding out of the pallet.  The drum was turned to prevent any further leakage.  Approximately 20 gallons of prodcut leaked from the drum.  Most remained in the trailer, less than one gallon leaked onto the cement loading are below. A spill response vendor was engaged to overpacked the drum and clean up the spilled product in the trailer and on the cement.  The event lasted approximately 30 minutes.
column169: Incident will be reviewed with employees and they will be reminded to examine pallets for hazards that could damage freight.

column168: Ashtae products is a verified shipper with Delta and ships hair beauty products to select destinations.  On this date, they tendered 9 boxes for transport to LGA.  Shipment was not declared as having any dangerous goods.  During the TSA mandated screening requirement, Delta discovered within one of the 9 packages an inner fiberboard box containing 6 bottles of "Ashtae Freeze Spray".  The markings on these bottles indicate "Caution:  Flammable.  Do not use near flame or while smoking.  Avoid spraying near eyes." Delta refused this shipment and our GSO operation advised Delta corporate Dangerous Goods Management Group.  We requested an MSDS from the shipper to evaluate whether the substance is regulated in air transport.  The MSDS indicated the flash point for the substance is 120F.

Today, 06 October 2007, we were tendered a shipment by Uti under airwaybill number 125-0318 8695. This master bill had several house airwaybills(HAWB) included, one of which is HOU 7974 9177. This house bill listed the contents as vending machines. Upon verifying the house airwaybill manifest and screening the cargo as required by TSA we discovered that this description was not accurate.    According to the documents attached to the HAWB and the MSDS, the shipment is actually something called a 'Permeation Tube'. The MSDS states that the content of these 'tubes' is in fact Hydrogen sulfide, UN1053. The transportation section of the MSDS states that transportation is forbidden for; passenger aircraft, railcar and cargo aircraft only.    At this time, 1030 AM local, I phoned; Jeff Lyter, Jim McCaffrey and Bill Ribeyro to inform them of the situation and that I was about to report to the FAA. They all concurred that the shipment be reported. I then phoned Dennis Juenemann who is our local FAA contact, leaving  a message on his voice mail. I waited until 1200 noon and then called Hazardous Material Specialist, Paul Klimas.    Mr. Klimas took down the information he requested and informed me that we had acted properly. He instructed me to keep the shipment and that he would be at our office on Tuesday, 09 October to begin his investigation.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was intransit between the pickup point and the origin terminal.  Upon arrival at the origin terminal, it was discovered that a container on the vehicle had leaked, allowing approximately 1/2 gallon of material to be released on the floor of the van trailer and onto the ground.  Facility personnel immediately donned appropriate protective equipment and initiated appropriate response procedures.  Upon identification of the damaged container, it was determined that a 55 gallon drum had shifted during transportation and tipped over, allowing the liquid to leak through the lock ring cover of the drum.  The response crew collected all spill material using a suitable absorbent material, decontaminated the trailer and disposed of it all spill materials along with the damaged drum.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the drivers will be re-instructed to insure that containers are loaded in such a way to preclude the potential for shifting during transportation.

column168: A Quality Distribution tractor-tanker suffered a leak from the frangible disc during transportation.  Approximately 20 gallons of material was released onto the soils and storm drain/drainage ditch alongside the roadway.  React Environmental responded to the site for cleanup and remediation of the area.  The leak was plugged and the tanker went an additional 5 miles to its final destination for offloading under the supervision of DEQ and React personnel.  The impacted area was neutralized and all waste was containerized for transportation and disposal.

column168: Driver was attempting a delivery of 7500 gallons of diesel into a tank that held 26000 galllons diesel.  The driver stuck the tanks and determined it had 81 inches of product in the tank. The driver called the dispatch and advised him of his concern that the product may not fit.  The dispatcher failed to provide the information needed by driver which was the conversion of 81 inches to gallons, instead the dispatcher told the driver it should fit.  The driver followed the instruction of the dispatcher.
column169: Reeducate dispatcher of the possible consequences of their decision and the importance of taking the time to get information and/or help from local terminal manager who are more knowledgable about the delivery sites in their area.

column168: At the Tree Top Cashmere, WA plant, Ron Noe (S&S Transportation delivery driver) was off-loading Sterileclean from a 330 gallon IBC into a bulk storage tank using a diaphragm pump. The Sterileclean is a ~12.5% sodium hypochlorite solution. Since we were initially unsure of the total amount of released material, we chose to report in the incident simply as a precaution. It is estimated that of the 30 gallons/299 pounds of released solution, there was approximately 37 pounds of sodium hypochlorite released (which is less than the reportable quantity).
column169: BHS Acquisitions and S&S Transportation recommend a dissemination of the details of this incident to all drivers. The discussion of this incident should review the off-loading procedure and remind all drivers of the importance of checking and double checking all deliver hoses and connections.

column168: On 10/8/07 a Univar driver was at a customer's dock and noticed product leaking out of his box trailer.  Product was noted to be sodium hypochlorite (12.5% solution), due to characteristic odor.  The rear of the trailer was opened and an IBC of sodium hypochlorite was found to be leaking from a small crack in the body just above the valve.  Approximately 30 gallons of product leaked from the IBC.  10 gallons were recovered in 5 gallon pails placed near the leak.  Approximately 15 gallons of the spilled material remained in the trailer and captured by spill absorbent material.  Approximately 5 gallons of product leaked from the trailer was caught by absorbent material placed in the customer's paved parking area below the leak.  Two employees were sent from the terminal to assist the driver with handling the incident.  The remaining product in the damaged IBC was transferred into another clean IBC.  The employees then cleaned up spilled material the trailer and the parking area.  The incident lasted approximately 3 hours.
column169: It is unknown how the crack occurred in the IBC.  The container was filled, stored, loaded without any leakage noted.  It was only noted at the first stop of the day for the driver.  So we surmise that the crack was made at some point in the container's past and only leaked due to the movement associated with the trip from the terminal to the customer location on this trip.  The crack was small and inside of the valve housing area of the tote making a visual identification of the leak difficult without removing the bottle from the frame.  Totes are inspected prior to filling, but this damage was missed.  The incident will be reviewed with operations employees (including drivers).

THE RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND WHICH LED HIM TO FOLLOW THE FLAMMABLE AND CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEETS. THE EMPLOYEE CALLED IN A PRECAUTIONARY INJURY AND THE PROPER SUPERVISORS WERE NOTIFIED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On 10/04/07 at 15:38, CSXT trainmaster Eric Pickel from the Osborn Yard in Louisville KY reported that a car inspector in the yard discovered tank car JRSX 785014 leaking Phosphoric Acid from the bottom outlet. Train Master Pickel went to the scene and found the top operated bottom outlet valve handle hanging from its securement chain on the top of the tank car. Train Master Pickel climbed the rail car, lifted the handle, placed it on to the valve stem, turned it two full turns and the valve was closed and leak stopped. Train Master Pickel estimates that less then one pint of liquid was lost. CSXT environmental Roger Marcum, and Pettit Environmental (a CSXT response contractor) arrived on scene to check the car. They found the leak from the bottom outlet had stopped. A closer inspection revealed that the bottom outlet cap was also less than tool tight and required two full turns with a pipe wrench to tighten. The car was released back to transportation for delivery to destination.                     NARRI :  2 (4+3+0) * (2+0) = 28  Cause Code = other 662 point 5  Top operated bottom outlet valve left open.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A BNSF carman in the railyard reported GATX 72843 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) with a top fitting vapor release and subsequent product trickle on the side shell of GATX 72843. GATX 72843 was cordoned-off in the railyard. BNSF Assistant Director of Hazardous Material responded and inspection revealed that the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured. Also, the inspection cover over the disc housing was missing. Responder replaced the frangible disc in kind and wiped off the small amount of spillage on the tank shell of GATX 72843. No ground impact from product spillage was evident. Response concluded prior to 0430 hrs. CDT, 10/10/07.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed APRX 6005 (DOT 113A90W tank car) venting argon from the side equipment/valve cabinet. APRX 6005 was isolated in the railyard awaiting further inspection. A BNSF contract responder inspected APRX 6005 and determined that the source of the argon vent leak was a pipe crack just below the threaded connection of the stainless steel piping on the labeled V4 valve line. A shipper responder welded the crack closed which eliminated further venting by 1830 hrs. CDT, 10/11/07.
column169: Car owner/shipper is addressing the pipe cracking issue with a modification to the valve lines to increase their flexibility to eliminate the line rigidity cracks.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported UTLX 812999 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard leaking from a top fitting. A BNSF contract responder was immediately dispatched to inspect UTLX 812999. The contract responder reported that the manway cover area was the leak source. Responder found two of the eight manway securement bolts less than tool tight. Inspection of the manway nozzle gasket revealed the gasket was deteriorated and broke in two when the responder removed it for a detailed inspection. The responder installed a new manway nozzle gasket and properly secured the manway cover. No spillage impacted the ground and the small amount of spillage on the tank shell evaporated. Response was concluded prior to 0240 hrs. CDT, 10/13/07.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

The shipper: Varied Industries Corp, was booked this dg cargo as Non-hazardous loads with us.  The undecared dg container was moved on the BNSF; from Minneapolis to Seattle - arrival at Seattle T5 terminal on 10/03/2007 PM.  Two days later, on 10/05/2007 AM, the shipper advised us that the container was contained hazardous substances.  On 10/06/2007, we confirmed with the Seattle terminal that the container had no placards.  10/08/2007, we received a copy of the dg declaration from the shipper.  However, this copy was missing part of the basic hazardous descriptions.  Therefore, we requested the shipper a proper copy of the dg declaration that was in compliance with the applicable regulations; for our use.  10/11/2007, we were succesfully be able to submit a final revised copy of the dg declaration (the 7th revision); after the shipper had been submitting a numerous revised dg declarations that were not acceptable by the regulations.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line by OOCL, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Kuala Lumpur Express from Long Beach to Yokohama.    The shipment was declared as three items of hazardous material - (1) Paint, Class 3, UN1263 (2) Extracts, Aromatic, Liquid, Class 3, UN1169 and (3) Aerosols, Class 2, UN1950 (Ltq Qty).    OOCL advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from Long Beach of additional hazardous material (Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, NOS, Class 9, UN3082) in the container that was not originally booked or otherwise identified.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the additional material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the additional item.    OOCL subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.      Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the additional hazardous material in the container.

column168: UTLX 200592 (DOT 111A60W7 tank car) was reported dripping product via the drip tube connection from the top valve trough during normal switching operations in the railyard. UTLX 200592 was carefully isolated in the railyard. All drippage evaporated. A BNSF contract responder inspected UTLX 200592 and reported that the 4-inch 80 psi frangible disc had ruptured. No replacement disc was readily available. A rubber ball was secured in the frangible disc orifice until a replacement disc was received from the shipper. On 10/24/07 a new frangible disc was installed and UTLX 200592 was released to proceed to its destination at 1155 hrs. CDT, 10/24/07.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: While delivering 3 drums of SULFURIC ACID 66B, 361330, with drum dolly, the Univar company driver observed the second drum was dripping more than the usual amount of water sometimes present on the top.    After standing the drum back upright, the receiving person at Precision Cast Parts provided a PH test strip and the liquid on the top was tested and determined to be a small amount (< 1 oz.) of Sulfuric Acid.  Upon further investigation, the bung was found to have been punctured in the center at some time -- as if for venting purposes, and was then re-used in error on the full drum of Sulfuric.    The customer had empties they were returning of the same product, so the driver replaced the bung with a good one, cleaned the top of the drum and delivered it to the customer.  Less than an ounce of product leaked on the top of the drum, and 2 drops hit the drivers boot -- no other spillage lost, and no injuries or damage were involved.
column169: Drum preparation process includes checking bungs and seals/gaskets; the inspection includes a check for bung integrity -- holes, threads, etc.  Ensure that the entire process is being followed and no short-cuts are taken during busy times.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: 10/16/07: At approximately 3:30AM, CR crew YPMO60, shifting cars in Fairless (PA) Yard for delivery to customers, noted tank car TILX 110133, load, Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top when moved.  Crew notified Morrisville (PA) Yardmaster, who in turn notified CR's S.T.O. and CR's Mgr. Risk Mgmt., A. Richter.    Conrail's emergency response contractor, REACT Environmental, Inc., was dispatched to the yard to investigate and mitigate.  Also assistance from customer representative, Basic Chemical Solutions, to which the car was being delivered.    Further inspection found eight of eight (8/8) liquid line mounting flange securement nuts/bolts not even hand tight; and, four of four (4/4) air line mounting flange securement nuts/bolts not even hand tight.  It was noted by both REACT and the customer representative that all twelve (12) bolts were made of stainless steel, but all nuts to secure same to flanges were of carbon steel.    All 12 securement nuts had to be strenuously worked to get them to operate as intended, due to the high level of corrosion due to incompatibility.  As the car was in the yard directly outside the intended customer's plant, the all nuts were resecured and made tool tight, so that the car could be moved without further incident into the plant.  Customer representative advised the securement nuts found on the car would be replaced after the car was unloaded and prior to shipment back out.      Car was also wiped down and decontaminated to safe levels (between 6-8 on pH scale) prior to Conrail moving the car into the plant.

column168: Report1  On 10/05/07 at 1716 Hours, in the CSXT Radnor Yard at Nashville TN. personnel found tank car UTLX 660983 leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated, CSXT Hazardous Material manager Jim Briski responded and found the car leaking product from the manway. Mr. Briski climbed tank car UTLX 660983 and discovered that three manway bolts less than tool tight. The three manway bolts were tightened with an 18 pipe wrench, the remaining manway bolts re-torqued and the leak was secured.  A CSXT contractor, SWS environmental Services, responded and wiped down the top and sides of the tank car of any remaining residue. The tank car were then released to destination. column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While on Interstate 40 Eastbound near mile marker 32 in Kingman, Arizona, the driver discovered a leak in the trailer.  The Tri-State Motor Transit Co. driver contained the release using paper towels.  H2O Environmental Technology, Inc. of Las Vegas, Nevada was dispatched to investigate the trailer, and perform the remainder of the cleanup.    H2O Environmental Technology, Inc. investigated the trailer and discovered one (1) leaking 55-gallon drum.  Apparently, the release occurred as a result of a faulty seam on the drum.  Approximately 15 gallons of free product were released.  H2O Environmental Technology, Inc. applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid inside of the trailer.  The leaking drum was placed into a 85-gallon over-pack drum and left on the trailer for disposition.  The contaminated absorbent material was placed into one (1) 55-gallon drum and left on the trailer for disposition.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Tri-State Motor Transit Co. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

On 10/10/2007 at 05:18 personnel in the CSXT yard in Russell KY yard discovered PPGX 77352, a residue tank car of chlorine, with a vapor leak. A CSXT train master inspected the area and advised that he could smell a slight chlorine odor within three car lengths of the car.  Greenup County 911, Weavertown Environmental and SPSI (CSXT Contractors) were all notified to respond. Five CSXT personnel reported effects from exposure to the product and were treated and released from a local hospital. At 06:42 CSXT was notified that the local fire chief had initiated a shelter in place advisory for the towns of Raceland and Russell, KY. At CSXT was notified the a fire department responder has fallen from the rail car to the ground, and was taken by ambulance to the local hospital for treatment.  Fire department personnel reported that they cut the seal off of the protective housing and closed all four valves a  of a turn. At 09:00 the shelter in place was lifted. Weavertown personnel then made entry to check that the 4 valves were secured. They found three plugs loose about 1 turn and one plug was loose 1  turns. SPSI arrived at 11:00 to investigate the release. Upon boarding the car the pressure was checked, 128 psi. The valves and plugs were checked for tightness. The car was sealed and released for transport.             NARRI :  5 (4+10+1) * (2+5) = 525  Cause Code = 301/ POINT VALUE =5

column168: We were traveling east on Bigstone Co. Rd. 2, pulling NH3 nurse tanks to the field.  The driver was traveling between 25 and 30 mph, when the tank started swaying badly from side to side, when he tried to get the vehicle slowed down the tank tipped over rolling into the ditch.  He called me right away, and we assured that there was noone, or nothing down wind that would be affected.  We then got a transfer hose and another empty tank next to the damaged tank and transferred the liquid into the good nurse wagon.  Once it was done we uprighted the tank, and bleed off the vapor.  The whole time this was going on, my supervisor traveled around the section, to ensure there was no adverse effects down wind.  When the pressure in the tank dropped, it released the excess flow valve on the damaged discharge valve, release the liquid reported.  We watched as the liquid evaporated, and once it was done, we loaded the trailer onto a flatbed and hauled to our shop.
column169: There wasn't any one thing that we could find that was done wrong.  Maybe one thing could be to go slower on gravel roads.  One thing that could be trained or taught, is how to pull a tank out of a severe swaying motion.  Meaning what to do when a tank starts to sway badly.

column168: On October 9, 2007 at approximately 0730 facility personnel at Clean Harbors Environmental Services’ 10-day in-transit storage facility located in Columbia, SC identified a minor release of a hazardous waste from a non-bulk package loaded onto a van trailer.  Upon the discovery of the release, a compatible container was placed under the trailer to collect any material being released.  The regional manager was immediately notified and a sub-contracted response crew was dispatched to identify the source of release and to initiate all necessary corrective actions.    Upon arrival, the response crew reviewed the shipping papers and donned appropriate protective equipment prior to entering the trailer.  Once inside the trailer, the response crew determined that the cause of the release was attributed to a 55-gallon non-bulk package containing Waste Corrosive Liquid Acidic, Inorganic n.o.s. that appeared to have pressurized and developed a small tear at the upper portion of the seam.  It is estimated that about 10 gallons of the corrosive liquid had escaped from the package with about 1 quart leaking from the trailer onto gravel below.  The leaking container was placed into a suitable salvage drum, and all of the released liquid was cleaned up utilizing compatible absorbent materials and pads.  The contaminated absorbent and the contaminated gravel was placed into an appropriate container for disposal at fully licensed hazardous waste management facility.
column169: Our investigation determined that the cause of the incident was a suspected chemical reaction within the drum that caused it to pressurize and tear at the seam.   The generators/shippers internal investigation confirmed that an incompatible chemical was inadvertently placed into the waste-stream that caused a reaction to propagate during agitation in transit.  The generator has implemented corrective actions to ensure that incompatible materials are not mixed together.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While attempting to fill an Above Ground StorageTank, approximately 100 gallons of free liquid were released due to over-filling. The free liquid impacted some standing water as well as a gravel/soil area. Apparently the release occurred as a result of the indicator not functioning properly. Praxair, Inc. personnel plugged a nearby storm drain using absorbent pads. Inland Waters Pollution Control, Inc. of Cleveland, Ohio was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Inland Waters Pollution Control, Inc. recovered the free liquid and impacted gravel and soil using a vacuum truck. Once all free product was recovered, Inland Waters Pollution Control, Inc. power washed the impacted areas. One vacuum truck containing approximately 600 gallons of waste water, and impacted soil and gravel was generated as a result of the incident. nland Waters Pollution Control, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence. However, Praxair, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: A BNSF crew in the railyard reported GATX 73050 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) emanating a vapor cloud from its top fitting area. GATX 73050 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. BNSF contract responders inspected GATX 73050 and reported finding the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured. The blown disc was removed and a new 165 psi frangible disc was installed. Responders used a neutralizing agent to neutralize the small amount of acid spillage on the side shell. No ground impact was evident. Afterwards GATX 73050 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: UTLX 204345 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product on its side shell that emanated from the manway nozzle area while this tank car was in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected UTLX 204345 and reported finding all the manway securement bolts tool tight. Further inspection into the manway securement revealed that the manway nozzle gasket was missing and this allowed the product to seep out from between the manway cover and the manway nozzle. The responder installed a new gasket and resecured the manway cover. Response was concluded by 1330 hrs. CDT, 10/25/07. No ground impact of product was readily evident. All spillage on the tank car side shell evaporated. No further spillage was noted or reported during subsequent railcar movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully documented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The shipment on pro# 473270663 arrived at UBG on the back of trailer 313-6475 with one five gallon drum tipped over and leaking. The drum was originally up aheadof two larger drums but since the freight was not secured or completely surrounded by dunnage, the five gallon drum moved during transit and tipped over. There wasonly two pieces of dunnage around the freight and none of the freight was tied to the wall. As a result of the freight tipping, one gallon of product spilled out on the floorof the trailer from the cap of the drum.
column169: To prevent reoccurence, the loader will receive additional counseling on proper loading procedures of hazardous products and receive appropriate disciplinary actions.The freight should have been tied to the wall and braced with dunnage and load bars and there were only two pieces of plywood around the shipment which didn't prevent movement of the product during transit.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading, one leaking 55-gallon drum was discovered inside of the trailer.  Approximately 40 gallons of free product were released and impacted some asphalt.  Apparently, the damage to the drum was due to being crushed by other freight during transit.  Lincoln Environmental of Ogden, Utah was dispatched to perform the cleanup.      Lincoln Environmental applied absorbent material to contain the free liquid inside and outside of the trailer.  The leaking 55-gallon drum was placed into a 95-gallon over-pack drum.  The contaminated absorbent materials were placed into twelve (12) heavy duty plastic bags for disposal.  Lincoln Environmental transported one (1) 95-gallon over-pack drum containing the leaking 55-gallon drum and twelve (12) heavy duty plastic bags of contaminated absorbent material to their facility in Ogden, Utah pending disposal coordination.      No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: IMTT-Bayonne personnel began to blow off the IBC and during that process product flowed from the AST into the IBC causing it to over flow out the PVRV. IMTT-Bayonne determined that human error was the root cause because the system was not designed with a check valve. A check valve was installed after the incident.  Additionally IMTT-Bayonne believes that the order of operations was a significant contributing factor on behalf of the operator since this operation has been conducted many times without incident.  The operator did not allow sufficient pressure to build within the IBC before openning the product valve.  IMTT-Bayonne engineers believe that installing the check valve should resolve both problems.

column168: (Report A) On Wednesday, October 10, 2007, at approximately 1230 pm, Train Q38009 derailed 31 cars heading eastbound which included NATX302127, containing Alcohol N.O.S. (ethanol).  Emergency Contractors Eagle Environmental and SPSI were dispatched.  A 1/2 mile radius was evacuated and nearby highways 2 and 44 were closed.  The car left the track rolling and oriented perpendicular to the track, laying on side.  The bottom outlet valve was sheared off with no leak. the car sustained head damage to A-side head with indention of about 24 inches in depth. The bonnet housing was crushed with no damage sustained to the valves.    There was a noted gash approximately 7" in length and 1/2" in width on the A-R side of the car with fire involved from ground contamination and surrounding cars.  Product had leaked from this area until a magnetic patch was secured after access was obtained on Friday.  The leak was also secured to prevent further loss while the car was being removed from the pile and staged for product transfer.  The car was re-staged, the product was transferred, purged and the car was cleaned on Monday 10/15/2007. Approximately 12-15k gallons of product recovered from the car.    (Report B)On Wednesday, October 10, 2007, at approximately 1230 pm, Train Q38009 derailed 31 cars heading eastbound which included TILX 190503, containing Alcohol N.O.S. (ethanol).  Emergency Contractors Eagle Environmental and SPSI were dispatched. A 1/2 mile radius was evacuated and nearby highways 2 and 44 were closed. The car left the track rolling east, and was found laying with the A end pointing south and slightly reclined about 15 degrees.  The liquid and vapor lines were sheared and contributed to fire and product release.  This car was involved with vapor fires emanating from these openings.  The car was situated perpendicular on the track listing towards the east with the manway in the 2 o'clock position.  The bottom outlet was partially opened less than an eighth and frozen in place from damage, also contributing to product release.  The b-end was pointing towards the north and the incurred significant damage to the underside where the car appeared to be creased.  Car was relocated and the remaining product transferred. The car was also purged and cleaned on 10/15/2007.    (Report C)On Wednesday, October 10, 2007, at approximately 1230 pm, Train Q38009 derailed 31 cars heading eastbound which included NATX300991, containing Alcohol N.O.S. (ethanol).  Emergency Contractors Eagle Environmental and SPSI were dispatched.  A 1/2 mile radius was evacuated and nearby highways 2 and 44 were closed.  The car left the track rolling South and was found laying on the B-Right side with the manway in the 3 o'clock position.  The bottom outlet valve was sheared off, with no leak.  First responders approached the car and noticed product leaking from the bonnet and opened to investigate.  They found the car to be leaking approximately 1-3 gpm from the vacuum relief devic

The car left the track rolling east, and was found laying with the A end pointing south and slightly reclined about 15 degrees.  The liquid and vapor lines were sheared and contributed to fire and product release.  This car was involved with vapor fires emanating from these openings.  The car was situated perpendicular on the track listing towards the east with the manway in the 2 o'clock position.  The bottom outlet was partially opened less than an eighth and frozen in place from damage, also contributing to product release.  The b-end was pointing towards the north and the incurred significant damage to the underside where the car appeared to be creased.  Car was relocated and the remaining product transferred. The car was also purged and cleaned on 10/15/2007. The bonnet housing was crushed with no damage sustained to the valves.    There was a noted gash approximately 7" in length and 1/2" in width on the A-R side of the car with fire involved from ground contamination and surrounding cars.  Product had leaked from this area until a magnetic patch was secured after access was obtained on Friday.  The leak was also secured to prevent further loss while the car was being removed from the pile and staged for product transfer.  The car was re-staged, the product was transferred, purged and the car was cleaned on Monday 10/15/2007. Approximately 12-15k gallons of product recovered from the car. column168: On Tuesday, October 16th at 0423 hours a Conductor working in the CSXT Cayce Yard reported finding signs of wetness and odors being emitted from Tank Car PLCX224620 (Load - Xylenes).  The area around the tank car was isolated. CSXT Management implemented their emergency response plan and notified the Cayce Fire Department.  Chemtrec was notified (Report Number 2007-10-16-00022) and the shipper, Eastman Chemicals / Vopak Terminals contacted.  Hepaco Environmental was contracted by CSXT to respond and secure the container.  Once on site, Hepaco representatives found the cause of the release was due to eight (8) of eight (8) manway securement bolts being less than tool tight.  Hepaco properly tightened the bolts and the container was tested for leaks.  The leak was secure and the railcar released to destination.  Less than two (2) gallons of product released.  Additional note: seal number N146014 was applied to one of the manway securement bolts.    Cause Code:  200  NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column42: ETHYL METHYL KETONE OR METHYL ETHYL KETONE
column168: On 10/20/2007, at 1015, train Q60919 derailed cars 3 through 8 and 18 through 35 in the consist along with 4 locomotives.  This car SOEX 2561, Residue Last Contained Methyl Ethyl Ketone, was the 26th car in the train.  The car was found upright and crossways to the track, with the bottom outlet valve missing from the car.  A small amount of product was observed dripping from the bottom outlet.  The car was moved out of the track area and a response contractor removed the remaining free liquid from the tank to prevent furrther spillage.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 10/22/07 at 2248 a Trainmaster at the CSXT Russell Kentucky yard discovered GATX 72763, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the local 911 dispatcher was notified. State and federal notifications were made. Weavertown Environmental, a CSXT response contractor was dispatched to the scene. The Raceland Fire Department were the first responders on scene, and the incident commander ordered a 1 mile shelter in place. CTEH, a CSXT air monitoring contractor was on scene and peformed air monitoring at the scene. No detectable concentrations of hydrochloric acid were found except on top of the car. Weavertown personnel attempted to fix the leak on top of the car and were unsuccessful. The incident commander then called for a two mile shelter in place and evacuated 27 homes next to the rail yard on Vine Street. CSXT Hazardous Material Mangers Tim Mannas and Jim Briski arrived on scene, made entry and found that three of the Fill Hole bolts were less than tool tight. The bolts were tightened and the leak was stopped. The shelter in place and the evacuation was lifted.            NARRI :  5 (5+5+0) * (2+4) = 300  Cause Code = 224
column169: No additional comments.

column168: 1st issue - shipper loaded larger hazmat ctn on top of a smaller non-hazmat ctn - thus - whatever was placed on top of frt could cause damage to frt because half of cans were sitting over edge of lower ctn, causing too much weight so that inner cans could not withstand pressure upon it.~~2nd issue -   origin terminal loaded a plt of heavy frt on top of plt that contained this hazmat shipment - amount of this excessive weight also contributed to failure.
column169: stress common sense procedures in loading freight - but also - shipping containers must also be stronger.   Common practice of shippers is to make the container as thin as possible to save costs.   Thin containers cannot handle stress during transit.

column168: On 10/17/07 at approximately 0730, a load of VM&P Naptha was being conducted at the head of Track #12. The loader attending the load failed to stop the pump upon reaching the desired amount of 7000 gallons. As a result the trailer overflowed causing a release of approximately seventy-five gallons of product. Fifty gallons of product was captured in a spill pan and approximately twenty-five gallons impacted the surface. All of the product was dammed and diked preventing it from entering the storm water system and/or the ballast. Product was absorbed with a non-combustible material (Sta-Dri)as instructed by the MSDS. Soiled material was then placed into an overpack drum and labeled as hazardous waste. A disposal service will be contacted to remove material from facility. Release was below the Reportable Quantity. Incident is being investigated further. Upon further investigation, it was determined that the quantity of product that impacted the surface was approximately ten gallons.
column169: Terminal personnel have been trained on proper loading procedures. High Level Alarms are now in use to assist in the prevention of another release.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Interstate 80, approximately 10 miles west of Wamsutter, Wyoming, the RRDF driver lost control of the vehicle, as a result of snowy weather conditions, which caused the truck to veer off the road into the median of the Interstate.  The Wyoming Highway Department responded to assess the site.  D&L Excavation was dispatched to assist in containment and cleanup efforts.  Upon arrival on site, D&L Excavation inspected the trailer, and assessed the damage.  D&L Excavation proceeded to commence in offloading the trailer.  Due to poor visibility and hazardous conditions, site was secured, until further cleanup/assessment the following day.  D&L Excavation returned to the site on October 22, and offloaded the damaged freight.  Four (4) 55-gallon drums of sodium hydroxide, solid, and one (1) 5-gallon pail of Ardrox Base Oil were discovered leaking.  Approximately 10 gallons of sodium hydroxide, solid, and 5 gallons of Ardrox Base Oil had released inside the trailer.  D&L Excavation also detected a minimal amount of diesel fuel, approximately 20 gallons, had released from the vehicle's tractor.  D&L Excavation overpacked the leaking containers and swept up the released product, which was containerized into recovery drums, pending disposition from the shipper.  D&L Excavation also excavated the impacted soil from within the median, which was transported for disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  Remaining freight was repalletized and shrinkwrapped, pending disposition.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release occurred as a result of a vehicle accident, caused by inclement weather, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Roadrunner Dawes Freight Systems, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: Driver/operator of the cargo tank did not check the level in the tank he was pumping into prior to unloading.  He was in the cab of the truck during unloading and didn't see that the tank was full and overflowing.  Approximately 3900 gallons were spilled into a fully contained and diked area.  Approximately 2500 gallons were immediately recovered.    As directed by GoeTek, the hazmat clean-up contractor hired, an excavator was employed to dig a trench outside the contained area for monitioring and containment of any leaching fuel.
column169: Not complying with policies and regulations is not tolerated at Western Co-op.  All drivers are trained and aware of the regulations for handling fuel.  Not checking tank levels and not attending to unloading is not acceptable.  Therefore, this driver is no longer employed with Western Co-op.

column14: CR NW 2001 (5 mi N of TX176)
column168: Transport driver was traveling southbound on CR NW2001.  Evidence at the scene indicates that the truck entered the curve traveling left of center.  The driver attempted to correct back to the right side and braked causing truck to roll onto its side.  A passerby was quickly on the scene and called for emergency assistance. The driver was taken to the hospital for observation and then released. Recovery crews were dispatched to the scene.  The load was tranferred to another truck.  A wrecker service uprighted the transport and removed off-site. Another crew returned the next day and cleared the loose debris from the road shoulder.
column169: Share accident investigation and findings with other drivers.  Express the importance of obeying speed limits and operating equipment at speeds safe for the load and road conditions. Incorporate training that addresses recognition and appropriate reaction to emergency situations.  Promote driving responsibly at all times.

column25: OOCL USA Inc. For Suttons International N.A. Inc.
column168: An eastbound BNSF intermodal stack train was reported by BNSF maintenance of way/signal gang working along the main tracks that an intermodal container riding atop an intermodal flatcar was leaking product. This train was stopped on the main track near MP 61 (Pomona, KS). IHAU 870701 (IM-101 tank container) atop flatcar BNSF 239602 was identified as the leaking container. The liquid commodity was leaking from the tank container's bottom. Contract responders constructed containment dams on both sides of the main tracks to contain spillage from IHAU 870701. BNSF and contract responders removed IHAU 870701 from the flatcar and placed it in a bermed containment area atop plastic sheeting. A vacuum truck was used to remove all remaining product from within IHAU 870701. The intermodal flatcar and IHAU 870701 were cleaned. Air monitoring and soil sampling were conducted. Traces of the product spill were reported along the track westward approximately 25 miles. Concentrated product spillage was absorbed with soda ash and Portland cement which included larger spill areas that were earmarked for soil excavation and disposal. All remediated impacted ballast and soil were staged for appropriate disposal. Some remediation activities continue as of this time. A BNSF inspection of the interior of IHAU 870701 revealed the breach as a crack in the tank. The crack was approximately 30 inches long and located about 30 inches from the tank's bottom, originating or terminating about five inches from the tank's head weld. The cause of the crack is under investigation. The decontaminated and cleaned IHAU 870701 container was trucked to the consignee's facility for further investigation into the tank's compromising crack.  Local authorities initiated an evacuation of 25-30 residences (approximately 40 people) within 1/2 mile on either side of the tracks at Pomona. The evacuation ended for most of those affected by 1630 hrs. CDT, 10/09/07; the exception being those people whom resided close to the site location.    The 16 member BNSF employee work gang working near the track that observed and reported IHAU 870701 leaking product were all taken to local hospitals for decontamination and examination.
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On October 27, 2007 at 11:45 personnel in the CSXT Richmond ACCA Yard discovered USLX21214, a (loaded )tank car of Flammable Liquid N.O.S (Crude Sulfate Turpentine)to have vapors leaking from the Pressure Relief Valve -Reclosing.  The car was moved and  isolated. Chemtrec and Meadwestvaco (the shipper) were notified. A CSXT response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found the Pressure Relief Valve was leaking from the 8 bolt flange gasket area. Meadewestvaco dispatched a contractor to respond to change out the gasket. The pressure relief device was unable to be removed. The car was isolated and the product was transferred to an empty tank car. The car owner (Millennium Specialty Chemicals) will apply for FRA movement approval to move the car to a home shop to be repaired.  Cause Code: 409  NARRI: 2(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 32
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 10/31/07 at 0954 personnel in the CSXT Louisville KY Osborn Yard, discovered UTLX 801551 a loaded tank car of Molten Sulfur had a strong odor coming from the top of the car. The car was isolated in the rail yard and the shipper was notified. A CSXT Hazardous Material Sentinel was dispatched to the scene. One of the man way bolts was less than hand tight, and seven of the remaining bolts were less than tool tight. The bolts were tightened with a pipe wrench , and the car was released for transportation                          NARRI :  2 (5+1+0) * (2+0) = 24  Cause Code = 200 /Point Value = 5

column168: A DOT inspector driving by a BNSF siding at Trentwood, WA observed a placarded BN 875099 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with a sizeable product stain on its side shell which appeared to be emanating from top of this tank car. BN 875099 was recently staged at this location for outbound train movement. The DOT inspector reported his observations to local BNSF mechanical management. BN 875099 was immediately inspected by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The inspection revealed that five of the six manway securement bolts were less than tool tight by three to four turns each. The responder tool tightened the loose securement bolts. Spillage on the side shell was evaporating. No further product release was reported for BN 875099 during transportation to its destination for unloading.

column62: Derailment; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: REPORT A- A BNSF train departing the siding through the south crossover to the main track at Arkansas City derailed ten railcars with six of these on their sides. The cause for this derailment is under investigation. Seven of the derailed railcars were ladened with hazardous materials. PTLX 220081 (DOT 111W100W3 tank car) derailed on its side and leaked a small amount of product via the vacuum relief valve (VRV). The VRV was not damaged or malfunctioning; and reseated itself shortly after the product release. PTLX 220081 was uprighted which ended any additional threatened product release from the VRV. A BNSF contractor remediated all spillage in the area.    REPORT B- A BNSF train departing the siding through the south crossover to the main track at Arkansas City derailed ten railcars with six of these on their sides. The cause for this derailment is under investigation. Seven of the derailed railcars were ladened with hazardous materials. NATX 71438 (DOT 111W100W1 tank car) derailed on its side and splashed product out from between the manway cover and the manway nozzle. Inspection of the manway securement by contract responders revealed that the manway securement bolts were 1/2 to 3/4 turn less than tool tight. The responders tool tightened the securement bolts ending further product release. NATX 71438 was uprighted afterwards. A BNSF contractor remediated all spillage in the area.

column168: EMPLOYEE HAS FINISHED FILLING AN AMMONIA NURSE TRUCK. HE PULLED AWAY FROM SCALE WITH A 2" FILL HOSE STILL ATTACHED. HE PULLED THE 2" VALVE OF THE TRUCK TANK. THE DRIVER PULLED THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF CABLE BUT IT FAILED TO CLOSE THE VALVES. EMERGENCY WAS CALLED AND EMPLOYEES EVACUATED THE BUILDING. THE RELEASE LASTED 10-15 MINUTES, BUT DUE TO COOL TEMPERATURES AND A WEATHER INVERSION THE AMMONIA CLOUD STAYED CLOSE TO THE GROUND. EMPLOYEES AND THE LOCAL VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT WENT DOOR TO DOOR TO EVACUATE PEOPLE. TWO SCHOOLS WERE EVENTUALLY EVACUATED AN STATE ROUTE II WAS CLOSED FOR 1 HOUR.
column169: 1)REVIEWED SAFE LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES FOR NH3 WITH ALL EMPLOYEES.    2)INMPLEMENTED A NEW PROCDURE FOR FILLING AMMONIA TRUCKS. KEYS WILL BE REMOVED FROM THE IGNITION. THE KEYS WILL BE PLACED ON A BOARD AT THE FILL HOSE STORAGE SIGHT DURING FILLING AND NOT REMOVED UNTIL FILL HOSE IS SECURED AT STORAGE SITE.    3)IMPLEMENTED NEW PROCEDURE FOR EMERGENCY SHUT OFF CABLE AND VALVE TESTING. AFTER LOADING EVERY AMMONIA NURSE TANK, USING THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF CABLE, THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF VALVE WILL BE CLOSED.    4)REINSTALLED THE QUICK DISCONNECT VALVE ON THE AMMONIA STOARGE LOAD-OUT LINE.    5) REDESIGNED THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF CABLE TO BOTH EMERGENCY SHUT-OFF VALVES SO THAT IT COULD NOT BECOME ROUND UP AND FAIL TO ACTIVATE THE VALVES.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS & PACKAGE FAILURE    DURING THE CRASH, THE IMPACT CAUSED A SEVERE SHIFT OF FOUR SKIDS OF BATTERIES. ONE SKID CONTAINED SEALED BATTERIES WHICH DID NOT SPILL. APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF OF THE BATTERIES ON THE REMAINING THREE SKIDS HAD TO THE POTENTIAL TO SPILL. THE BATTERY CAPS PREVENTED THE ACID FROM FLOWING ONTO THE GROUND UNTIL THE BATTERIES WERE UP RIGHTED BY THE HAZMAT CERTIFIED CLEAN UP CREW. APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF BATTERY ACID MAY HAVE LEAKED FROM THE VEHICLE.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS/ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.    THE CRASH CAUSED CONDITIONS NOT "NORMALLY INCIDENT TO TRANSPORTATION" (REFERENCE 177.834). THE PRESENT CONFIGURATION OF THE SKIDS IS SUFFICIENT TO MEET ALL BATTERY PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS IN 173.159.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering unleaded gasoline at a customer location. As the driver was unloading, gas began to leak out of the premium vapor valve. The driver immediately shut of flow of product but approximately 5-7 gallons had spilled onto the concrete. No product reached soil or drains. The spill was cleaned up with spill pads and litter. Circle K environmental was notified. The premium load had not yet been delivered and the stick and veeder root reading both showed that the tank could hold 2266 before reaching the 90% and therefore should not have leaked. Circle K management was notified of the problem and performed maintenance to clean out the line.
column169: Circle K management was notified of the problem and took full responsibility. Maintenance was performed to clean out the lines. Lines need to be regularly maintained to avoid backups and leaks.

column168: On 10/24/2007 at 2154 hrs, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard in Cincinnati, OH discovered GATX63223, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid Solution leaking from the top of the car as it approached the the top of the hump. Two CSXT personnel reported exposure to acid vapors from the car as it approched the switch point at the top of the hump, and both were transported by ambulance to the hospital and treated for injuries. The car was isolated and the shipper, Basic Chemical, OH EPA, Cincinnati Fire Department and Chemtrec were notified.  Veolia Environmental and CTEH, both CSXT response contractors, were dispatched to the scene.  Veolia Services assessed the car and noted less than three gallons of product on top of the car.  The PRD inspection cap was missing and cable appeared to have been cut, leaving the top of the rupture disk exposed.  The rupture disk was broken allowing the product to slosh out.  CTEH was notified for air monitoring and contracted Summitt Environemental to respond.  Veolia perfromed area and air monitoring with no detectable conentrations of hazardous materials around the car or at the hump location.  CSXT Manager of Hazardous Materials, Bill Caton responded to collect the top appurtneces and assist in replacement of the rupture disk assembly.   Decontamination of the car surface was performed by Veolia. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.  Cause Code:  441  NARRI:  2(5+5+0) X (2+7) = 180

column168: The driver for the nuclear pharmacy was returning to Wichita Falls, Texas. The driver had made his final delivery inAda and was returning with returned doses from the previous Friday. The driver veered into the oncoming lane oftraffic and struck an oncoming semi-truck carrying a load of gravel head-on. The driver did not survive. TheOklahoma DEQ sent 2 investigators who helped the pharmacy RSO recover all material. The first responders, driver,transportation containers and storage pigs were all surveyed and showed no signs of contamination. Wipes andsurveys were done on the vehicle and no contamination was noted. The ammo boxes were damaged and the innercontainers were not all contained. Four inner containers were damaged but no syringes were damaged and the vialswere still in tack. The pharmacy repackaged the material and removed it from the scene .
column169: We are planning additional driver inservices dealing with driver alertness. This being our first experience of thisnature, we believe all procedures were followed properly. All of the documents in the vehicle were filled out properlyby the driver and helped the first responders by showing them exactly what was being transported. The bracing in thevehicle and the delivery packaging was compromised due the the magnitude of the impact although I believe theproper packaging and bracing did prevent any ultimate contamination.

column168: Univar driver, Paul Swisher, delivered a tote of Sodium Hypochlorite 12.5 % to ChemResearch.  The Univar truck was parked in the street as there was no room to back into the customer's yard - this is a normal unloading process for this customer. The Chemresearch employee took the tote from the back of the Univar flat rack trailer, lowered the tote, backed up and turned then drove forward towards their building.  The forklift's front tires started to go across a water culvert in the road which made the tote fall forward off of the forks. The 2" vent bung popped out of the tote and five gallons of product then came out of the 2" opening until the tote was uprighted.  The Univar driver immediately placed four absorbent pillows taken from his truck Emergency kit, on the spill to assist in containing the leaking product.  At the same time the Chemresearch employee uprighted the tote with his forklift.  Chemresearch employees then proceeded to clean up the spill. No product went into any storm drains.
column169: 1. When possible (when there are no cars parked at entrance) the delivery truck will back into customer site     2. The tote will be unloaded from the side with the teeter bars if available.    3. A strap, which will go around the tote and be secured to the forklift backrest, will always be used when unloading to assist in preventing the tote from falling from the forklift.

column168: Driver began filling heating oil tank at customer. The previous driver overfilled the tank causing fuel residue to remain in the vent pipe. As the second driver began filling the tank, the escaping air through the vent picked up the residue remaining in the pipe, causing the residue to escape out the vent, spraying the side of the building. Residue amounted to around 4 gallons. OSI Environmental was called for response and cleanup. Cleanup and remediation was completed the same day as the release. Customer was made aware of the vent problem (should have drained back in to the tank), the vent pipe is obviously bent.

column169: ALL DRIVERS ARE PERIODICALLY INSTRUCTED AND REMINDED ABOUT SPEED AND OPERATION OF TANK TRUCKS WITH LIVE LOADS. IT WAS AGAIN EMPHASIZED THAT SPEED NEEDS TO REDUCED IN CURVES, OFF RAMPS AND TRAFFIC CIRCLES. DISCUSSION WAS ENCOURAGED AND THE MEETING LASTED UNTIL ALL QUESTIONS WERE ANSWERED. DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED TO PROCEED A MINIMUM OF 10 MPH SLOWER THAN POSTED SPEEDS IN RAMPS AND CIRCLES, THIS WAS AGAIN DISCUSSED AND DIRECTED.

The driver was stopped for speeding and as he and the AZ DPS Officer was doing a walk around they noticed a drip coming from out around a bolt hole for the internal value. Upon repair it was found thegasket had a slit malfunction causing the drip out around a connecting bolt.

Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc Driver was delivering LSD to a customer location. While unloading the driver tripped over the fitting causing it to come loose. As the product was flowing, fuel began to leak from the coupling. The driver immediately shut off flow of product but approximately 30-35 gallons escaped. The Brevard County fire department responded as did the DEP. The fuel was contained in an overflow drain and concrete pad. No fuel entered soil or storm drains.
column169: Driver was re-trained on unloading procedures. Driver re-viewed unloading videos and was counseled by safety personnel. Incident prevention observations were conducted on driver.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering unleaded gasoline to a customer location. Prior to unloading the driver was backing the vehicle in place and struck a concrete pole. The incident caused the tank unloading heads to be ripped open. The damage resulted in approximately 130 gallons of fuel spilling. The driver immediately began to help control the spill. The local fire department and SWS First Response came to the scene. Approximately 2-3 gallons entered the storm drain. The fire truck dumped 500 gallons of water into the drain while SWS used a VAC truck to clean it out.
column169: The driver was terminated for failure to follow safety procedures, which include looking behind the truck before backing. All company drivers were reminded of proper driving procedures in the monthly safety meeting.

column169: Proper securement of freight is was discussed with all necessary freight handlers to help prevent another occurrence.

column168: One of our employees was driving into an outbound trailer to load sixe (A) cartons of paint related materials. As he was driving into the trailer he was raising his forklift blades to place the small pallet of cartons on a load deck. The load deck was roughly six (6) feet from the tail of the trailer, so he was drivig over the EOD (edge ofdock) ramp while raising the freight. The freight bounced slightly as the employee rolled over the EOD causing the freight to shift and fall off the pallet. Upon further inspection we found that the freight was not secured properly to the pallet, although upon first glance it appeared to be very secure. THe freight fell about three (3)feet, didn't damage the outer cartons, but popped of the lids of the paint related material along with denting the cans slightly causing the leak. Relaes lasted about ten minutes ans was cleaned up using floor dry. Used floor dry was placed in a used floor dry container. Total estimated time was thirty (30) minutes.
column169: The shipper should have wrapped the freight to the pallet, on all four sides. The freight was tide down on one corner and wrapped on the opposite corner.

Upon arrival, SPSI personnel found the leak was due to a broken "breather stone". CSXT contacted shipper representative R. Hill, who arranged for delivery of a new "breather stone' to T. Mannas, CSXT Hazmat Manager at Wiilard, OH.Mr. Mannas received the "breather stone" on 10/19/07 and, along with personnel from Eagle Construction & Environmental Services, Inc., Findlay,OH, removed the defective "breather stone" and replaced it with the "breather stone" furnished by the shipper. column168: FREIGHT NOT SECURED IN TRAILER - ONE BOX FILL AND HIT THE GROUND CAUSING A LEAK.

The shipper loaded our trailer and sent our driver to their scales to weigh heavy.  It was at their scales that product was observed dripping out of the overflow tubes.  Our unit was sent back to the loading rack where their personnel opened the dome lid and checked the dome gasket.  They reported to us that the dome gasket was cracked so they replaced it which stopped the leak.     We asked plant personnel to forward us the failed dome gasket or a picture of the same but as of this writing, we havent received it.  Plant personnel cleaned up the small spill with absorbant material and disposed of themselves.
column169: Reinterated with all of our tank cleaners to check and double check all gaskets in each trailer as they are cleaned or replaced to assure that leaks like this are prevented.      Our drivers are not allowed on top of our trailers in this plant so the gasket could have fallen out of the track and was pinched instead of being cracked.  We ask our drivers to perform a slosh test within the various shippers facilities to identify a problem if any before getting out on the open highways.

column168: Container was secured to side of trailer by way of ratchet straps and e-tracks in the side of the trailer.  one of the bolts was loose on the e-track which caused it to protrude out from the wall of the trailer.  the drum was placed up against this bolt has was secured against it.  As the vehicle traveled through it's route. The contaier rubbed against this bolt head until it finally wore a small hole into the side of the container just above the lower support ring.  Material slowly ran down the side of the drum and onto the floor of the trailer.  Driver discovered leak when he arrived at a customer to unload material.  Driver Noticed that material was dripping from side door.  Driver placed absorbent material on ground to prevent material from spreading, driver also placed overpack drum underneath trailer to catch dripping material.  E.C.I., an Emergency Response company, was dispatched to the sceene. Leaking container was discovered, placed on it side to prevent any further spillage.  Balance of material from leaking container was placed into  overpack drum, spilled material was cleaned up with absorbent material which was containerized as well. Both the overpack and absorbent material were returned to Shipper. Contents of overpack was transfered to another container and weighed to determine amount of material loss.  Loss was approx. 6 gallons. Good material was recovered, damaged container and absorbent material sent off site to an approved TSDF for dispoal.
column169: Shippers loading personnell have been reminded to inspect trailer condition prior to loading.

column168: Driver of tractor and cargo tank trailer was attempting to make a left turn from Highway US36 into 1-35 Southboundon ramp. Driver of combination units was travelling at 20mph and was too fast for conditions as the unsettled liquidsurge cause the cargo tank to slowly roll over onto its right side and pulled the power unit with it. They both ended upresting against the guardrail of the the on ramp. The cargo tank sustained damaged to the shell at the 13:00 o'clockposition and began leaking product Sodium Chlorite Class 8, UN1908, PG II until the level of product in the tank fellbelow the cracked shell. Approximately 9000lbs of product flowed out of the tank in the first 3 hours. The emergencyresponse company Hulcher Services arrived on the scene and began to dyke the area of the runoff and contain anyadditional spillage to the immediate area of the intersection. Soil was excavated containing the spilled liquid anddeposited into two roll off boxes that were sampled and sent off site for disposal at a secured landfill facility. A smallquantity of oil from the engine and fuel from the tractor tanks was also spilled onto the highway and recovered into 3recovery drums. They were also sent for disposal to a secured TSD facility.
column169: This accident has its root cause in driving too fast for conditions. Instead of coming to a full stop at the highwayentrance and proceeding to turn left, the driver slowed down and attempted to manoeuvre the turn at too great a rateof speed and could not keep the cargo tank unit on its wheels. Once the unit began to lift off the highway the drivercould not recover and he lost control of the combination unit and ended up on its side. Fluid dynamics in cargo tanktraining as it relates to driving around sharp curves would certainly have provided additional awareness and mayhave prevented this unfortunate incident all together.

column168: VTR's daily train RD-BD hauling 25 cars, traveling Northbound at 1 Imph had a rail break underneath the train This caused the track to tear up, derailing 4 salt cars and the 15 loaded gasoline cars, and then rolling on their sides The "tight lock" couplers on the tank tram, and being that the train stopped in such a short distance(80 ft), the forward sloshing motion of the gasoline was also a contributing factor causing all 15 cars to roll on their sides. The tank cars did not rupture Due to the cars twisting as they rolled on their side this caused the man way hatch to break the seal on cars GATX 66350 andGATX 44586 . The other cars were in tact but leaking minimally at the tank train interconnection hose shut off valve.The release began at 1355, all leaks were under control, either stopped or contained in 12 hours.Cars # GATX 66350 and GATX 44586 were immediately pumped off into tank trucks, and the other cars were completed pumped off in by 1000 on 10/23/07Immediate response had containment booms and dikes along the river bank to catch spill. Agreed for safety purposes by the Haz Mat Team not to contain gasoline on site, but allow to enter river Once leaks were contained or stopped the protective booms were maintained along the river to absorb any seepagefrom the rain Absorbant material was used to clean up any residue on the ground at spill area.VTR hired a local environmental firm to work with the State and EPA for final cleanup and mitigation of spill area, including soil removal if necessary.
column169: The VTR has been operating the tank train since the mid 70's with out incident, however, it is evident that the tank train concept works Both the locking couplers and the interconnected hoses between cars in conjunction with valves at the end of each car, when shut acts as a single car. In this circumstance they worked perfectly, keeping the product in the cars even though some of the interconnect hoses had been damaged.VTR is taking additional measures to have an electronic consist of each train containing hazardous materials that leaves the yard, in the hands of the dispatcher. Hence, allowing the dispatcher to fax or email the Fire Department if necessary.From this experience , we need to prequalify environmental haz mat response company. Just because they have a license does not mean they are prepared tohandle a situation of this magnitude.

ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALSl PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE  COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. A BNSF southbound train taking siding off the single main track derailed several railcars in the siding with some fouling the single main track. Shortly afterwards, a BNSF northbound train on the main track struck the rail equipment fouling the single main track which resulted in the derailment of the northbound train's two locomotive units and its head 22 railcars. Included in this derailment of the northbound train was UCLX 30002 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) that came to rest in a slanted upright position atop other derailed rail equipment and sustained several breaches to its tank car shell. The B-end head sustained a large dent in the upper left head quadrant with a large peel tear in the head metal which allowed a large volume of product to escape. Also in the B-end head were two one inch puncture holes within the lower right head quadrant. The A-end side shell sustained a 3 inch by 3 inch puncture hole as well. It was estimated that the majority of the commodity within UCLX 30002 was lost. UCLX 30002 was cleaned and purged on site. BNSF contract responders applied lime to the ground spillage to neutralize the acid spill. Neutralized impacted soil was later excavated and staged for appropriate disposal.  Approximately 350 to 400 residents in the southwest portion of Clara City were evacuated. The evacuation ended at 1600 hrs. CDT, 10/29/07. An overpass (MN State Highway 7) which runs over and is perpendicular to the main track and siding was closed until MN DOT officials inspected this structure for damages.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Valve Open
column168: During normal switching operations in the railyard, NATX 38195 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported with a fresh product stain on its side shell. NATX 38195 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting inspection. A BNSF contract responder inspected NATX 38195 and reported finding the leak origin from under the sealed protective housing cover. The liquid valve was approximately 1/2 turn open which was caused by the valve's handle movement after contacting the inside of the protective housing cover when the cover was closed. The responder closed the valve, removed the valve handle and secured the handle to the closure plug chain. The tool tight closure plug on this valve was the leak source and the product seepage at the plug connection stopped when the valve was closed. The responder tried to remove the plug for inspection but couldn't without damaging the stainless steel plug. The plug threads may have been cross threaded or galled. All spillage evaporated. This response was concluded by 1945 hrs. MDT, 10/29/07. NATX 38195 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard to await further repairs. The shipper arranged for a new replacement liquid valve assembly to be sent to Denver and installed. Valve replacement was accomplished on 11/13/07 prior to 1650 hrs. MST without further incident. Afterwards, NATX 38195 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: This two piece shipment was opened after the customer dropped off the shipment duet o suspicious behavior from the previous week, (see employee statements). Inside was what appeared to be what is believed to be fireworks. As the shipper had not offered the shipment with any dangerous goods markings or labels, nor with a shipper's declaration for dangerous goods, it was believed to be undeclared dangerous goods. FAA agent David Hansen was notified and the shipment was held pending his investigation. David took part of the shipment contents with him for his investigation. The shipper later provided a Material Safety Data Sheet which listed the contents as Articles, explosive, n.o.s., 1.4C, UN 0351 for rocket motor reload kits.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: Shipment 125 3373 4212 of 24 pcs at 564 kgs was accepted at British Airways World Cargo in lAD on October 23, 2007 at approximately 1800 hours. Shipment was listed as a consolidation containing seven house airwaybills all listed as containing personal effects. Shipment was x-ray screened and prepared for transportation via truck from Washington to Atlanta. Shipment arrived in British Airways Cargo in Atlanta on the 24th of October and was prepared for uplift on a B747 freighter aircraft from Atlanta to London departing on October 25th. Shipment departed Atlanta to London on the 25th of October. On October 29, the shipment was prepared to be loaded in a ULD in London and it was discovered to have one box leaking. Upon further investigation of the leaking, it was discovered that this box contained an automotive battery. The area was closed off and a clean up crew were dispatched to properly clean the area and this was completed. The box containing the battery was part of HAWB JFH-10710058 is currently held in British Airways London Heathrow operation for investigation by the CAA.
column169: ALL STAFF HAVE BEEN BRIEFED ON THE IMPORTANCE OF CHECKING FOR UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS IN CARGO AND ALL SHIPPERS MUST DECLARE ANY SHIPMENTS REGULATED FOR TRANSPORTATION BY AIR.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On October 15, 2007 Ron Dougherty was leaving the Warwick branch at approx. 4:00am tomake a delivery to New York Power. As he drove down River Street, he made the turn onto Howe Street and the blow valve on tanker 933 was not closed all the way causing Hypochlorite to leak out of the blow off line leaving a white residue streak on Howe Street.  The white streak was noticed by one of our plant operators who then notified me immediately. We sent two of OU plant operators, Jeff Payne and Jeff Oliver up to Howe Street with buckets of water to clean the hypoclorite residue off the road. As they started to clean the residue one of the residents approached Jeff Payne and let him know that they called the Fire Dept.which Lt. Hagan pulled up to the seen as they were talking. Jeff let Lt. Hagan know what happened and then he came back to the branch to get me.  I (Scott Mann) met with Lt. Hagan at the scene and he asked what we recommend they do and I told him we were going to flush the residue with water. Lt. Hagen said he was going to check w/Orange County to*
column169: *SEE WHAT THEY SUGGEST, WHICH WAS FLUSH THE RESIDUE WITH WATER. BEFORE LEAVING THE YARD, EVERY DRIVER IS REQUIRED TO DO A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering gas to a customer location in Norcross, GA. While unloading the scheduled 4500 gallons of ULSD, the driver noticed that fuel began to leak out of the top of the tank into the containment area. Driver immediately shut off flow of product but appoximately 30 gallons had spilled. The spill went into the containment area but due to previous damage to containment area a small amount did make it into soil. No fuel reached drains. The product integrity sheet was signed by customer management and they accepted full responsibility for the spill and clean-up.
column169: Driver watched unloading procedures video. Customer must be aware of order and current tank levels prior to signing integrity sheet. Customer repaired the containment area to avoid future spills into soil.

column168: * This event was an Undeclared Hazardous Material shipment only. There was no incident, release, evacuation orpackaging failure. On Monday, October 29, 2007, Sandia National Laboratories (SNL) Receiving Department received / accepted a box from Aberdeen Proving Ground. After an examination of the contents, it was concluded that the box contained an Undeclared Hazardous Material. A review of the MSDS confirmed that the contents of theshipment was Methyl Phosphonic Dichloride (9.5 grams), of which is a Poison-by-lnhalation (PIH), 6.1(8), PG I, ZoneB. After researching this material in the Transportation Regulations, it was determined that this material was shippedby air incorrectly. The package did not have the proper marking or labeling and the package did not include theappropriate shipping paper.
column169: The Shipper / Offerer was notified by the SNL Shipping Department to cease any further shipments to SNL until further notice. The Shipper / Offerer was notified of the appropriate shipping requirements for the material andinformed that an Hazardous Materials Incident Report would be filed due to the manner this package was shipped to SNL. In addition, a requirement was instituted that prior to any future shipments to SNL, the Shipper/ Offerer shall communicate with SNL customer and an agreement reached regarding the shipment of material, time frame of theshipment, and manner of shipment to prevent any future recurrence.

column168: Peach State Labs, Inc. was delivering IBCs to various customers in Dalton, GA. After the first delivery, atapproximately 9:19 a.m. our driver was detoured to a non-typical route due to road construction. This route included a large hill at the north end of VD Parrot Pkwy. After stopping for traffic, the driver accelerated causing the tractor to shake. This shaking caused 3 - 275 gallon IBCs of Autoacid A-80-N to shift in the truck breaking the load lock andsliding out of the truck onto the road. Driver immediately circled back around and contacted 911. 2 of the 3 IBCs were leaking from the top closure and significant damage was noted on all IBCs from fall. Dalton Fire Departmentresponded to contain leaking product. Marion Environmental Services responded on behalf of carrier to perform remediation and cleanup. Approximately 200 gallons of Autoacid A-80-N leaked. The spill was neutralized and cleaned up by Marion Environmental Services.
column169: Peach State Labs, Inc. has purchased additional higher capacity load locking devices and has revised box truck loading procedures to ensure against future load shifts. The leakage from the IBCs was minimal considering damage sustained during fall. No corrective actions are necessary for IBCs.
