column168: Container MATU 249437-7 was opened for inspection at the BNSF Railroad, because it contained hazardousmaterial. They removed seal # SPICT 732226, but noted that seal# MATU 123577, which was the seal of record wason the floor inside the container. BNSF rejected the load because of the seal discrepancy and because theydiscovered 2 boxes of fireworks had been ripped open in what we think was an attempt to pilfer. The SPICT seal isconsistent with Shanghai Pudong International Container Terminals, the terminal it came from in China, therefore weassume the alleged attempt to pilfer took place before it left China. Matson sent the container to us to for evaluationand correction. We opened the container and discovered a large inspection hole in the center of the plywood andblocking & bracing. Two of the cartons had been ripped open, but the weight of the cartons above preventedremoval of the roman candles. Matson contacted the consignee and they Fedexed 2 new cartons to us. Weremoved the blocking & bracing and the 2 cartons, transferred the roman candles to the new cartons and replacedthe blocking & bracing. Matson paid the trucker $285.00 to round trip the container between BNSF and our yard andwe charged $285.00 to rework, block & brace the load.
column169: We suggested to Matson that they advise the shipper to cut smaller inspection holes in the plywood which are onlyslightly larger than the hazmat stickers. This would make it very difficult for anyone to rip open a carton in an attemptto pilfer and is all that the BNSF requires for inspection purposes.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MW PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING

column168: At approximately 3:10pm on October 31, 2007, a tri-axle dump truck was traveling westbound on Route 78 near milemarker 31 in New Jersey. A passenger vehicle, a Ford Taurus, that was traveling westbound in the right lane, forunknown reasons changed lanes striking the tri-axle dump truck on the right side. Both vehicles veered left off theroadway into the median. The tri-axle rolled over. The inner shipping container tore as a result of contact with theother vehicle, releasing a portion of the contents of the container onto the median. Following the incident,appropriate notifications were made to emergency response personnel including a call to 911 and the contact of ourhazardous materials cleanup contractor, Rapid Response, Inc.Rapid Response, Inc. initiated and directed the cleanup and remediation efforts related to the hazardous materials.The hazardous material that was released was a solid that was discharged on a soil embankment. A large portion ofthe material release could be recovered. However, the cleanup included the removal of contaminated soils. Allmaterials were properly packaged at the site and transported from the scene for shipment to the original consignee.The following responded to the scene... NJDEOT, Somerset County Hazmat, Bedminster Fire and Rescue, RapidResponse, Inc., a hazmat cleanup contractor, NJDEP, Gemini Towing, and Horwith Management personnel.
column169: Based on the reports taken at the scene, the incident was generally caused by the unforeseenactions of a third party, consequently, we believe that the driver was unable to avoid the collision.The incident occurred in a construction zone. The edge of the road was not grated and asignificant drop-off was present along the roadway. It is our recommendation that the road edgeshould have been tapered to prevent such an abrupt drop, therefore, preventing the likelihood ofa rollover.

column168: At 03:04 PM on 10-11-07, Frank Lerch, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Cohen Ford, Yardmaster, reported tank car FPAX 931129 had released a small amount of product onto the side of the tank car.  Car was located on the north end of Track 17 in the Settegast Railyard, Houston, TX. Mr. Ford further advised there was no product impact to the ground and there were no drains or waterways impacted and no reported injuries resulting from this release. Mgr. Lerch responded to the scene and requested the RMCC make shipper contact via Chem-Trec. On arrival and inspection of the car, Mgr. Lerch noted that  the frangible disk in the safety vent assembly had been ruptured. Lerch replaced the frangible disk with a similar 1 651b disk, cleaned the sides of the car with a neutralizing solution, and released the car to continue onto destination without further incident. While inspecting the car, there were no signs indicating the car had been mishandled. Cause of the disk failure unknown. At 04:45 PM, Mgr. Lerch spoke to shipper represenative Robert Laughlin, day supervisor for Formosa Plastics, and advised him of the release, and corrective actions taken.

At 06:51 AM on 10-12-07, Frank Larch, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Tim Crabtree, Director of Terminal Operations, reported loaded tank car HOKX 8286, located in bowl track 63 to be leaking from the bottom of the car n the Englewood Railyard; Houston, TX,, Mile Post 357.0 of the Terminal Subdivision. Mgr. Lerch responded and requested the RMCC make shipper notification via Chem-Trec. On arrival, Mgr. Lerch noted product leaking from the bottom of the car around the sump due to car liner failure. Car was leaking at a rate of approximately 1/2 gallon per minute. Upon determining source and cause of the release, Mgr. Lerch placed a containment pool below the car to contain the release. Mgr. Lerch then contacted consignee representative Tim Lancelin, Hazmat Manager for Oxy Vinyl, advised him of the release, and requested he dispatch response personnel to the area for further handling of the car and remediation of the site. Additionally, Mgr. Larch dispatched personnel from Center of Toxicology & Environmental Health to conduct air monitoring. At 07:30 AM, Mgr. Lerch spoke to shipper representative Bart Lambert, day shift shipping supervisor for Occidental Chemical. Mgr. Lerch advised Mr. Lambart of the release, that the spill had been contained, the consignee had been contacted and arrangements were being made to off load the car into tank trucks, and remediate the area. At 09:57 AM, tank car HOKX 8286 was moved from Bowl 63 to Track 112 so that full yard operations could resume. CTEH personnel were on site providing air monitoring. Matt Allen, Texas Commission Environmental Quality and Tim 0 Brien Regional Manger of Hazardous Materials were on site as well. Approximately ten gallons of product had been released from the tank car, and was neutralized under the supervision of the TCEQ, with no drains, waterways affected, and no reported injuries. At 04:43 PM, off loading operations began. Due to complications, off loading activities were delayed, and would continue throughout the evening, and into the following day. At 09:00 AM on 10-13-07, United States Environmental Services Contractor arrived to assist in the transloading operation. At 12:30 PM on 10-13-07, transloading operations were complete, Oxy Vinyl and United States Environmental personnel were in the process of repairing the car, and remediating the surrounding area. Denise Seals, Manager of Environmental Held Operations, was on site, and was provided a turnover of the incident to oversee further site activities, and to relieve Mgr. s Lerch and O Brien. At 04:50 a patch was applied to the tank car, but would require further work prior to moving the car to home shop. Personnel cleared the area and the car was left on site for further handling. On 10115/2007 at 03:56 PM additional patching of the car was completed. The car was then moved to a spotting track within the yard awaiting billing to move the car to home shop for repair. Arrangements were then made to reduce the load and clean the car. Upon completion of reduction, and cleaning of car, It was released to continue onto destination without further incident. There were no drains, waterways impacted, or reported injuries resulting from this release.

column168: No package failure; Vandelism by a suspected previous employer. Rear internal & external valves were cracked open to allow product to slowly drain out of trailer. A driver showed up shortly after to p/u the trailer and discovered the product leaking. He immediately shut it off & reported the incident to his Manager & 911 was called. DEHAC was involved, a report filed with NRC, Sherriff's Dept, & Fire Dept. DEHAC has since arrested the suspected individual on 4 counts. Contact was made with Art Ramsey of the Fed DOT, and a letter was faxed to him on 11/09/207 by me stating that this was called a "pre transpotation function" and that this property is not an authorized transfer station. He said that he needed this so he could decide if the DOT needed to investigate. I did as he instructed.
column169: Loaded or empty trailers are no longer parked at this location. This form 5800.1 was not filled out because I thought that this was classified as a "pre transpotation function", but after a discussion with a lady at the Haz-Mat Information Center (800-467-4922) on 03/14/2008, I was advised that I needed to go ahead & fill it out anyway.   She has also instructed that in the future I should file one of these reports right away, and then if it is really not required of me, then it can be changed. Our company is currently pricing cameras for our Terminals for security, and no tankers loaded or empty will be left on this property again. This property was locked, but access was still comprimised.  Again I apploigize for not filing this report earlier, but I assumed it was not required since the trailer was parked on our yard; I have since learned different.

column168: Traveling on a gravel lease road with S curves on a down grade with a 90 degree turn to the right. A third party pick up with gooseneck trailer was parked in the road limiting the turning area. Driver was distracted by the pickup, arid In making sure he did not hit the pickup/trailer they dropped the wheel of the hazmat trailer. Soft shoulder pulled the trailer down a 40’ cliff at approximately a 70 degree angle.   Tote caps were not tightened sufficiently to prevent residual fluids from leaking. Absorbent booms were put In place once it was logistically possible to enter the contaminated area, and a third party environmental clean up service was contacted for remediation.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 10/07/2010 at 22:15 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Radnor yard in Nashville, TN, discovered GAMX 9335, a loaded tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous, leaking from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard away from CSXT employees, and the shipper was notified thru CHEMTREC Report 2010-10-08-00001. Angie King 813-261-0600, representative for the shipper,Transammonia, responded to the call. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered product was leaking from the pressure relief device. HEPACO secured the leak by replacing the O rings on the pressure relief device cap. The leak was secured and the car was released to destination.     This incident did require a special switch move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is required for this incident.     Cause Code: 414  NARRI Code: 5 (4+9+2) x (2+0) = 150
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The pail was unloaded with leakage noted.  Examination of the pail revealed the pail had a loose cap/lid and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap/lid was secured. Undamaged product was returned to the shipper.  The damaged product was properly disposed of in accordance with Federal Regulations.

The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
